<HEADLINE>
Camera Store Ripoffs
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<POST>
<POSTER> tjones5@________.com </POSTER>
<POSTDATE> 2007-08-29T14:53:00 </POSTDATE>
I will never go to another camera store.  It amazes me how these
places stay in business.

I have a 3 year year old digital camera that suddenly stopped working.
I took it to a local camera store to inquire about getting it
repaired.  As soon as I showed it to the guy he handed me a form to
fill out.  After I filled it out, he told me that the camera would be
checked and I would get a repair estimate.  If the camera was
repairable, they would fix it, and the cost would be anywhere from
$100 to $200.  He stuffed my camera in an envelope along with the form
I filled out and said I had to pay $50 downpayment, of which half
would be applied to the repair costs if I decided to do the repair,
otherwise I'd just be out the $50 and the dead camera would be
returned to me.  At this point I told him I would not pay the $50 and
I'd just take the camera somewhere else for repair.

Then this guy shows me a new camera and tells me that mine is obsolete
anyhow, and for $289 I could buy this new one.  I knew at this point
that it was time to leave the store.  I quickly looked at the new
camera and made a mental note of the model number and left the store.

I went to Walmart where I found the exact same camera brand and model
on the shelf for $129.  I later called another store and found they
had this same model for $135.

If this is what these camera stores do (rip people off), I will never
step foot in another one.

By the way, my so-called &quot;obsolete&quot; camera took excellent pictures and
was compatible with any PC computer.  I am going to see if I can get
it repaired by the factory or another place other than a camera store.

Tim
</POST>
